<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-697-164  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 697 164.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  July 30 1990 n601 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CRT safety questioned. (includes related article on Sigma Designsmonitors with reduced low frequency emissions)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Doherty, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer and monitor makers met in San Jose, CA, to discussconcerns about potential health harms from CRT screen extremelylow frequency (ELF) electromagnetic field emissions.andP;  Althoughelectromagnetic fields are known to influence biological systems,no health hazard from the fields has been determined.andP;  Computerfirms want more research into ELF emissions to determine safetylevels.andP;  No US government standards exist for CRT emissions, soconcerned companies use an imprecise set of standards developed bythe Swedish government.andP;  The testing equipment employed in readingemission levels is sensitive to ELF radiation from other sources,such as wiring and electric appliances, so determining CRTemissions and their influence is difficult.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CRT DisplaysElectromagnetic RadiationMedical IssuesStandardsIndustry-Sponsored ResearchConferences and MeetingsMonitors.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>